LogFileDescription.Description: Non parseable section that gives details about logfile sections that require any clarification. Legend array contains the labels and the paths of the mentioned sections and examples or description of the registered data. RGS protocol API provides a method to add custom per-protocol additional fields to the CustomProtocolLegend section.

Legend.Label: Header:RgsInfo:RgsMode
Legend.Data: RGS@Home, RGS@Hospital, RGS@RehabCenter, RGS_Research.

Legend.Label: Header:ProtocolInfo:ProtocolMode
Legend.Data: UpperLimbsTable, UpperLimbsStanding, EquilibriumStanding, Hands, Cognitive, Addiction

Legend.Label: Header:ProtocolInfo:TrackingDevice
Legend.Data: Kinect V2, Kinect Azure, Leap Motion, Oculus hand tracking

Legend.Label: Header:ProtocolInfo:Condition
Legend.Data: Specify any patient condition relevant for the understanding of the data within the logfile (paretic side, gender). For security reasons, the patient's profile only can be recovered from MIMS with adequate permission. RGS protocols' API provide a method to add here more fields if needed

Legend.Label: Header:IRC
Legend.Data: Intelligent Rehablitation Controller is the component for adapting the RGS protocols adaptation to user's performance. Refer to the technical documentation of the corresponding version for additional details.

Legend.Label: Header:IRC:UserModel
Legend.Data: The model aims to predict the difficulty parameters of the protocol by matching the user's actual performance to a target performance. Whenever possible, the model relies on weights obtained from the user’s past sessions of this protocol. All the data collected in each call of the difficulty algorithm is sent to the cloud and computed offline to produce a new user model that will be used in the next session.

Legend.Label: Header:IRC:UserModel:PredictedPerformance
Legend.Data: The performance parameter that the user model will try to predict

Legend.Label: Header:IRC:UserModel:DifficultyParams
Legend.Data: The associated parameters that affect user's performance

Legend.Label: Header:IRC:UserModel:UserWeights
Legend.Data: Weights of each layer of the perceptron network that define the user model

Legend.Label: Header:IRC:UserModel:DefaultWeights
Legend.Data: A generic cloud-based model that might be generated by the IRC without requiring any sample data of the current user.

Legend.Label: Header:CommonEvents
Legend.Data: List of RGS built in events. These events are present in all protocols and cannot be changed.

Legend.Label: Header:ProtocolEvents
Legend.Data: List of the protocol-specific events that can happen independent of any human-computer interaction. Their occurrence is logged in. Could be seen as temporal cues.

Legend.Label: Header:ObjectEvents
Legend.Data: List of the protocol-specific events that concern human-object interaction, and therefore can include interaction specific information, which is logged in.

Legend.Label: Data:CommonEvents:IrcComputeDifficulty
Legend.Data: Event triggered every time that difficulty adaptation is performed. The output is a set of difficulty parameters that are mapped to interactive elements in the protocol and change its difficulty. The algorithm tries to converge to a performance estimation within a given range. This estimation is later checked against the user's actual performance.

Legend.Label: Data:CommonEvents:IrcComputeDifficulty:Performances
Legend.Data: The output of the adaptive difficulty computation.

Legend.Label: Data:CommonEvents:IrcComputeDifficulty:Performances:[]:AlgorithmDescription:Method
Legend.Data: Can take four values 'UserWeights', 'DefaultWeights', 'Heuristic' and 'Override'. UserWeights': Predicts performance for a given set of difficulty parameters based on the user's previous sessions if they exist. 'DefaultWeights': If the UserWeights fails its prediction or does not exist, a model based on the cloud data of all similar patients that trained with the same protocol is used. 'Heuristic': If bothUserWeights and DefaultWeights fail their prediction or do not exist,  a basic direct linear model assigns high/low performances to low/high difficulties. This method is always available.'Override':The difficulty parameters can always be set manually by an administrator (therapist) regardless of the user’s performance.

Legend.Label: Data:CommonEvents:IrcComputeDifficulty:Performances:[]:AlgorithmDescription:PredictionTarget
Legend.Data: The user's target performance for which the difficulty computation tries to compute the respective difficulty parameters.

Legend.Label: Data:CommonEvents:IrcComputeDifficulty:Performances:[]:AlgorithmDescription:MinPredictionAccpetanceThreshold and MaxPredictionAccpetanceThreshold
Legend.Data: The range within which the performance prediction of the difficulty computation is accepted. If the IRC's prediction falls out of this range, the method will fallback to other methods (see Method) which might give better predictions.

Legend.Label: Data:CommonEvents:IrcComputeDifficulty:Performances:[]:AlgorithmDescription:DifficultyParameters::Key
Legend.Data: Name of the difficulty parameter

Legend.Label: Data:CommonEvents:IrcComputeDifficulty:Performances:[]:AlgorithmDescription:DifficultyParameters:Value
Legend.Data: Normalized value of the difficulty as calculated by the IRC.

Legend.Label: Data:CommonEvents:IrcComputeDifficulty:Performances:[]:AlgorithmDescription:DifficultyParameters::Mapping
Legend.Data: Transformation of normalized value which is mapped to the interactive elements in the protocol.

Legend.Label: Data:TrackingRaw
Legend.Data: Raw tracking data as captured by  the sensor. Distances in meters.

Legend.Label: Data:Kinematics
Legend.Data: Mapped kinematics in the virtual world. Distances in meters.

Data.Description: All the input and output parameters for the user model described in the previous section have normalized values from 0 to 1. Protocols have to map them into virtual world related magnitudes (distance, velocity, times,...) This section describes how all these mappings are made. As a general rule, units in virtual world correspond with their real world counterpart (for instance 1 meter in the virtual world corresponds with 1 meter in the real world).

ProtocolMapping.Desc: Avg hit time from all pucks from current wave for each hand
ProtocolMapping.Mapping: Summatory of wave puck hit time / total wave hitted pucks
